If the roots of $ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d = 0$ are $\alpha$ and $\beta$, and $\gamma$, then we can re-write the equation in factored form as $a(x - \alpha)(x  - \beta)(x - \gamma) = 0$

Both these equations should be equal as both of them have the same roots.

$\begin{align}
ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d &= a(\overbrace{x - \alpha)(x  - \beta})(x - \gamma)\\\\
a(x^3 + \dfrac{b}{a}x^2 + \dfrac{c}{a}x + \dfrac{d}{a}) &= a(x^2 -(\alpha + \beta)x +\alpha\beta)(x - \gamma) \\\\
x^3  \purpleC{+\dfrac{b}{a}}x^2 \maroonD{+ \dfrac{c}{a}}x + \tealD{\dfrac{d}{a}} &= x^3 \purpleC{-(\alpha + \beta + \gamma)}x^2 +\maroonD{(\alpha\beta +\beta\gamma + \gamma\alpha)}x \tealD{- \alpha\beta\gamma}
\end{align}$

On comparing coefficients of $x^3$ , $x^2$, $x$ and $1$, we get:

$\begin{align}
\purpleC{(\alpha + \beta+\gamma)} =  \text{sum of roots} &= \purpleC{-\dfrac{b}{a}}\\\\
\tealD{\alpha \beta\gamma} =  \text{product of roots} &= \tealD{-\dfrac{d}{a}}\\\\
\maroonD{\alpha\beta + \beta\gamma + \gamma\alpha} &= \maroonD{\dfrac{c}{a}}
\end{align}$

