To find $BD$, we need to find $\blueE{QD}$. We can find $\blueE{QD}$ using a proportion from similar triangles.

###Setting up a proportion

Corresponding sides of similar triangles are proportional, so we can set up and solve a proportion:

$\dfrac{\blueE{QD}}{QB}=\dfrac{CD}{AB}$

We picked side $\blueE{\overline{QD}}$ because we need to find its length.

We picked side $\overline{QB}$ because it corresponds to side $\blueE{\overline{QD}}$.

Then we picked another pair of corresponding sides where we already knew the measurements.

$\begin{array}{rcl}
&\triangle CDQ
\\
{\text{adjacent to } \atop \angle 1/\angle 2}
&\overbrace{\underbrace{\!\!\!\!\!\left\{ 
\dfrac{\blueE{QD}}{QB}=\dfrac{CD}{AB}
\right\}\!\!\!\!\!}}
&{\text{opposite to } \atop \angle 1/\angle 2}
\\
&\triangle ABQ
\end{array}$
